First possible method.

Corona$polyarchy_cat=factor(Corona$polyarchy_cat)

Possible Intepretation:

If we observe the values of the coefficients (intercepts and slopes) and the relative plots, even at first glance there appears to be a positive correlation between countries with considerable levels of democracy (based on the indices of democracy the datasets referred to) and the number of (reported) Coronavirus cases. However, from these data alone we would not go as far as suggesting, as of now, a relation of causation. Furthermore, as the regression lines on the plots and the slopes observed in the summaries would suggest, those values do not differentiate that much from one another, standing just slightly above or below the value of 2. Albeit we cannot talk yet of causation, these results may suggest that a democratic regime may be less efficient to tackle down the spread of the virus due to social, cultural and legal norms that are, often times, totally absent in non-democratic regimes, where the use of military and police force is less restricted and scrutinized.

First Solution, as suggested in the HW.

Addition of population (2018 data) as a control variable. cases_log=β0+β1v2x_polyarchy+β2popdata2018+ϵ

abline(lm(Corona$cases_log ~ Corona$v2x_polyarchy+Corona$popdata2018), col = "maroon")

As observable both in the summary of this lm and in the relative plot, it appears that directly adding the population as a control variable in the function, does not help the investigation here attempted. In fact, as the summary shows, for the control variable popdata2018, the value of the slope is basically zero, showing thus no correlation. As we shall see now, adopting the second solution suggested in the HW, normalizing the number of cases will instead provide some clarification, helping us in our endeavour.

Second Solution.

Normalizing the number of cases by dividing the number of Coronavirus cases by the population size (in 2018) and using it as our new dependent variable.

Corona$norm_case=Corona$cases_log/Corona$popdata2018_log

OLS_m6=lm(norm_case~v2x_polyarchy, data=Corona)

summary(OLS_m6)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = norm_case ~ v2x_polyarchy, data = Corona)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -0.30767 -0.10060  0.01564  0.10220  0.30345 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value             Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)    0.26082    0.02589  10.075 < 0.0000000000000002 ***
## v2x_polyarchy  0.23846    0.04378   5.447           0.00000019 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.1369 on 160 degrees of freedom
##   (1 observation deleted due to missingness)
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1564, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1511 
## F-statistic: 29.67 on 1 and 160 DF,  p-value: 0.0000001901
plot(Corona$v2x_polyarchy,Corona$norm_case)

abline(lm(Corona$norm_case ~ Corona$v2x_polyarchy, data = Corona), col = "green")

As we can observe from the summary and the plot, by normalizing the number of cases with the population data, our results are more near to those we found in the first three functions that compared the number of cases with the different types of democracy, and indeed even in this case, the existance of a correlation is indeed confirmed.

Once more, from the summary and the plot we can observe that as a control variable, the population does not appear to possess a considerable direct correlation with the normalized number of cases, as we have already noted earlier for the number of corona cases. This suggests that a stronger relation of correlation exists between the type of regime a country possess and the related number of (reported) Coronavirus cases, where population represents a relevant data only if properly considered to normalize the number of (reported) cases.
